The Run Scored, At Bats, Doubles, and Walks are a good variables to contribute.There is a positive coefficient in these variables and their p-values are less than 0.05. The Home Runs and Strike Outs are negative coeeficients and their p- values is ≤ 0.05.¶

This model has a high R-squared (0.681) which means that this model provides a better fit to the data. It's hard to comment about the adjusted R-squared which is slightly different (0.676 ) because it doesn't change much.The adjusted R-squared doesn't not tell much.¶

As we add one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, and eight variables R- squared doesn't change much.The F statistic (184.9) is significantly higher than 1 which is really good.The p-value is less than and equal to 0.05 for Run Scored, At Bats, Doubles, Walks, Home Runs, and Strike Outs; therefore, there is a strong realtionship among Games Won, Run Scored, At Bats, Doubles, Walks, Home Runs, and Strike Outs. Among these six values, Run Scored, At Bats, Doubles, and Walks have a positive values. The Home Runs and Strike Outs have a negative values. Therefore, the best one will be chosen among Run Scored, At Bats, Doubles, and Walks. The Doubles' p-value is far less than 0.05. Therefore, the best one will be chosen as per Doubles.¶

x intercept: The model indicates that Games Won chance decreses as Run Scored, At Bats, Doubles, and Walks, independent variables increase.¶

x intercept: The model indicates that Games Won chance decreases as Home Runs and Strike Outs decreases.¶

The Hits and Triples p-values are grater than 0.05. Therefore, there is a 95% confidence interval which includes 0.Therefore, there is no relationship among Games Won, Hits, and Triples. As a result, these values are rejected.¶
